          "body": "Verse 8 is one of the most striking lines in the Psalter: 'I will awaken the dawn.' David does not wait for morning to bring praise; he rouses himself to praise before morning arrives. The triple use of ur (awake) — 'Awake, my glory! Awake, harp and lyre! I will awaken the dawn' — describes a comprehensive self-mobilization for worship. Every faculty is summoned: kavod (the soul, his honor), the material instruments, and time itself. This is the discipline of preemptive praise — praise that does not wait for vindication before it begins. The NIV Study Bible notes that 'my glory' in verse 8 is likely David's own soul or spirit, the faculty that distinguishes him as made in God's image, now called to its proper function of glorifying its Maker. Tim Keller (The Songs of Jesus, 2015) points out that this kind of sunrise-preempting praise is only possible for someone who has already settled the question of God's character — you cannot will yourself to praise if you are still uncertain whether the God you are praising is actually trustworthy. The steadfast heart of verse 7 is the prerequisite for awakening the dawn of verse 8."
