          "body": "The psalm's final movement (vv. 9-11) expands from the individual cave to the entire human community. 'I will give thanks to You, O Lord, among the peoples; I will sing praises to You among the nations.' The man who opened by taking refuge alone in the shadow of God's wings (v. 1) closes with an intention to praise before all peoples (am) and all nations (ummah). The missionary logic is implicit but unmistakable: what God does for the individual — chesed great to the heavens, emet reaching to the clouds (v. 10) — is news the whole world needs to hear. The exact repetition of the refrain at verse 11 ('Be exalted above the heavens, O God; let Your glory be above all the earth') confirms that personal deliverance and cosmic doxology are not two different agendas. The same glory that sheltered David in a cave deserves to be acknowledged by every nation on earth. Paul cites the structural parallel in Psalm 108 (drawn from this psalm) in Romans 15:9 as scriptural evidence that the Gentiles are included in the praise of God — the cave-Psalm becomes a missionary manifesto."
