        "number": 2,
        "title": "Chesed and emet dispatched from heaven — God's character as rescue",
        "range": "57:3-4",
        "excerpt": "He will send from heaven and save me; He reproaches him who tramples upon me. Selah. God will send forth His lovingkindness and His truth.",
        "body": "Verse 3 is the psalm's doctrinal anchor, and its syntax rewards close attention. God 'reaches down from heaven' (*shalach*, stretches out, dispatches) and saves David — and then, as the verse continues, shalach appears a second time: 'God sends forth His lovingkindness and His truth.' The parallelism argues that the rescue and the attributes are not merely related — the rescue *is* the chesed and emet made visible in historical event. What God dispatches toward the endangered individual is His own covenant character.\n\nChesed and emet are the Psalter's most stable theological pair, appearing together in Psalms 25:10; 40:11; 61:7; 85:10; 86:15; 89:14; and 115:1. They constitute the content of God's self-disclosure at Sinai (Exodus 34:6-7 — 'abounding in lovingkindness and truth') and are the attributes the Psalter returns to whenever it wants to ground assurance in something more durable than circumstances. Emet in this context is better rendered 'faithfulness' than 'truth' — it is the reliability of the God who keeps His word. Peter Craigie (Psalms 1-50, WBC) notes that the two attributes form a hendiadys: loving faithfulness, faithful love. They cannot be pulled apart without distorting both.\n\nThe Selah after verse 3 is a liturgical pause — the congregation or the reader is invited to stop and absorb the weight of what has been declared before descending into the nightmare portrait of verse 4. The pause is theologically significant: the declaration of chesed and emet must be heard before the lions are described, or the description of the lions overwhelms the declaration.\n\nVerse 4 names the enemies with four weapons: lion-imagery (*levi*), ravenous fire (*lahat*), spear-and-arrow teeth (*chanit / chets*), and sword-tongue (*cherev*). The escalation from animal to weaponized body parts describes a total threat environment — the enemy is both beast and battle, and the most dangerous weapon is the tongue. This anticipates the New Testament's treatment of *lashon* as the member that sets the whole course of life ablaze (James 3:6). In David's context, the false accusations circulating about him — that he was treasonous, dangerous, worthy of death — were precisely the sword-tongue Saul's court wielded against him.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalach* (send, reach out) appears twice in v. 3 — once for rescue, once for the dispatch of chesed and emet; the repetition is structural. *Chesed* — covenant loyalty, steadfast love; *emet* — faithfulness, reliability, truth. *Lahat* — flaming beasts or ravenous ones; *chanit*, *chets*, *cherev* — spear, arrow, sword."
