        "body": "Verse 5 interrupts the enemy portrait with a doxological refrain that will close the psalm at verse 11. Its placement is interpretively crucial. It appears before the crisis is resolved — enemies are still out there in verse 4, and in verse 6 they are still setting traps. The refrain is not a celebration of accomplished rescue; it is a declaration of what the psalm is ultimately aimed at regardless of how the crisis ends. Derek Kidner (Psalms 1-72) observes that by placing the doxology mid-crisis, David is doing what the entire shape of the psalm argues: the exaltation of God is not the conclusion of the story — it is the framework within which every chapter of the story is to be read.\n\nVerse 6 describes the enemy plot in three steps: they spread a net for David's feet; his soul was bowed down (*nephesh kaphaph* — the soul bent under weight); they dug a pit before him. Then the pivot: 'they themselves have fallen into the midst of it.' The reversal is described in past-tense certainty before any visible rescue has arrived — this is the Hebrew perfect of confidence, the grammatical form for events so certain in God's purposes that they are treated as already accomplished. Proverbs 26:27 generalizes the principle: 'He who digs a pit will fall into it.' Psalm 7:15-16 uses the same imagery.\n\nThe second Selah follows the reversal. The pause comes at the moment of maximum irony: the hunter has fallen into his own trap, and the soul that was bowed down is about to declare itself steadfast. The Selah holds the reader in that threshold moment — the turning is real, but it has not yet been verbalized. What follows after the pause is the psalm's most important declaration.\n\nReformed and Arminian commentators agree on the interpretation of verse 6's reversal: it is not David's doing but God's providential governance of events (cf. Romans 8:28). Where they may differ is on the mechanism of the individual's perseverance: whether the steadfast heart of verse 7 is preserved by irresistible grace (Reformed) or sustained by a believer's faithful cooperation with sufficient grace (Arminian). Both camps affirm that the outcome glorifies God and is dependable for the one who cries to El Elyon.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rum* (be exalted) — lifted high above; *kavod* (glory) — the weighty splendor of God's observable presence. *Kaphaph* (bowed down, despondent) — to bend under load; *kun* (prepared, established) — the same root that describes both the enemy's trap (v. 6) and David's heart (v. 7)."
