        "excerpt": "My heart is steadfast, O God, my heart is steadfast; I will sing, yes, I will sing praises! Awake, my glory! Awake, harp and lyre! I will awaken the dawn.",
        "body": "Verse 7's double declaration — 'my heart is steadfast, O God, my heart is steadfast' — is the psalm's emotional and theological climax. The repetition is not mere emphasis; it is a formal self-announcement in God's presence, the equivalent of taking a solemn position. The Hebrew *lev kun* (heart established, fixed) describes a heart that has been anchored — not because the danger has passed, but because the one to whom the heart is anchored has been named: El Elyon, the God who accomplishes all things, the One who dispatches chesed and emet. Spurgeon (Treasury of David) notes that this declaration immediately generates action: 'I will sing, yes, I will sing praises' (*shir, zamar*) — the two primary Hebrew praise-verbs, both volitional futures. The steadfast heart is not passive; it produces worship.\n\nVerse 8's triple awaken (*ur, ur, ur*) is one of the most energetic lines in the Psalter. Every faculty is summoned: kavod (the soul/glory — the image-bearing center of the person), nevel (harp), kinnor (lyre), and shachar (dawn). The last clause — 'I will awaken the dawn' — reverses the normal order of human experience: morning wakes the person. David will wake the morning. Praise is not a response to circumstances; it is a force that acts on time itself. Calvin (Commentary on the Psalms, 1557) interprets this as David's determination to let nothing — not darkness, not danger, not sleeplessness from anxiety — delay the moment of praise. The instruments are to be ready; the soul is to be ready; and if dawn hasn't come, praise will summon it.\n\nVerses 9-10 widen the scope to the nations. 'I will give thanks to You, O Lord, among the peoples; I will sing praises to You among the nations.' The Hebrew *am* (peoples) and *ummah* (nations/peoples) encompass the full breadth of humanity beyond Israel. The theological logic is clear in verse 10: the reason for universal praise is the universal scope of chesed and emet — 'great to the heavens,' 'to the clouds.' What sheltered one fugitive in one cave is cosmically wide. Paul cites the parallel text (Psalm 108:3) in Romans 15:9 to argue that David's praise-among-the-nations language anticipates and prefigures Gentile inclusion in the worship of Israel's God. The cave psalm is a missionary psalm.\n\nThe refrain of verse 11 repeats verse 5 verbatim and provides the interpretive frame for the whole. What was asked as petition in verse 5 ('Be exalted... let Your glory be') is now confirmed as proclamation. The worshiper who began by asking has been transformed into one who declares. The cave has not changed; the enemies have not disappeared; but the man has been turned — from chasah-taker (refuge-seeker) to ur-er (dawn-awakener), from petition-maker to nation-praiser. That transformation is the psalm's deepest pastoral argument: the same God who is the destination of desperate prayer is the subject of the widest possible praise, and arriving at praise does not require waiting for the cave to end.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Lev kun* (heart steadfast) — to be established, fixed, settled; *shir* and *zamar* — the two primary praise verbs. *Ur* (awaken) — triple imperative in v. 8. *Shachar* (dawn) — used metaphorically; the personified morning. *Am* and *ummah* (peoples, nations) — all humanity beyond the covenant community. *Kavod* in v. 8 refers to David's soul/spirit, not God's glory — the image-bearing faculty called to its proper function."
